<h3 class="text-wine-700 font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Appearance and Visual Cues</h3>
<p>Rosé wines display a captivating spectrum of pink hues, from the palest salmon-tinged "onion skin" color of Provence rosés to the deeper copper-rose shades of wines with extended skin contact. The color intensity directly correlates with winemaking technique—lighter styles result from brief skin contact (2-24 hours), while darker rosés may involve the saignée method, where juice is "bled off" from red wine fermentation. Quality rosés should appear brilliant and clear, with medium-minus viscosity creating gentle legs that indicate moderate alcohol and glycerol content.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700 font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Aromatic Profile</h3>
<p><strong>Primary aromas</strong> burst with fresh fruit character: wild strawberries, white peach, watermelon rind, and pink grapefruit dominate lighter styles, while deeper rosés reveal red cherry, raspberry, and blood orange. <strong>Secondary aromas</strong> from fermentation contribute subtle yeasty notes and occasionally a whisper of lactic creaminess from malolactic conversion. Premium aged examples develop <strong>tertiary complexity</strong>—dried rose petals, orange blossom, and delicate spice notes that add sophisticated depth without overwhelming the wine's inherent freshness.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700 font-semibolic mt-6 mb-3">Palate Structure and Texture</h3>
<p>Most rosés present medium-minus to medium body with vibrant acidity that creates mouthwatering freshness—typically 6-7 g/L total acidity. Tannins remain barely perceptible, contributing subtle grip rather than astringency. Alcohol levels usually range from 11.5-13.5%, providing warmth without heaviness. The texture should feel clean and refreshing, with a silky mouthfeel in premium examples.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700 font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Flavor Development and Finish</h3>
<p>On the palate, rosé wines typically echo their aromatic profile with additional complexity. Expect flavors of <strong>red berries</strong> (strawberry, raspberry), <strong>citrus</strong> (pink grapefruit, mandarin), and <strong>stone fruits</strong> (white peach, nectarine). Mineral undertones appear in wines from limestone soils—think wet chalk or river stones. Herbal notes like dried Provence herbs or white pepper add savory complexity in food-friendly styles.</p>

<p class="bg-wine-50 p-4 rounded-lg">The finish should be <strong>clean and persistent</strong> but not overly long—typically 30-45 seconds in quality examples. Look for a refreshing aftertaste with lingering fruit and mineral notes, avoiding any bitter or cloying sensations that indicate poor winemaking or excessive residual sugar.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700 font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Quality Markers</h3>
<p>Premium rosé wines exhibit <strong>aromatic intensity</strong>, <strong>balanced acidity</strong>, and <strong>complex layering</strong> of fruit, floral, and mineral elements. The best examples maintain freshness while offering depth—avoiding simple or one-dimensional profiles that characterize mass-market styles.</p>

