  <h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Color Reveals Production Method</strong> - When selecting rosé, examine the hue to decode quality and style. Pale salmon indicates saignée method from premium red grapes like Pinot Noir, while deeper coral suggests direct press Grenache or Syrah. Avoid bright pink wines with purple tinges—these often indicate inferior bleeding method or artificial enhancement. The most elegant rosés show copper-orange highlights, indicating proper phenolic extraction.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve at Precise 45-50°F for Optimal Expression</strong> - Unlike white wines that can handle colder temps, rosé's delicate fruit aromatics shut down below 45°F and become flabby above 50°F. Chill for exactly 90 minutes in refrigerator or 20 minutes in ice bath. At proper temperature, you'll taste the wine's full spectrum from red fruit brightness to mineral backbone—crucial elements often missed in over-chilled bottles.</li>

  <li><strong>Skip the Decanter, Embrace Immediate Service</strong> - Rosé's charm lies in its fresh, reductive character—decanting actually diminishes these qualities by introducing oxygen that mutes delicate floral notes. Pour directly from bottle to glass, and if serving multiple bottles, open them sequentially rather than all at once. The exception: vintage Champagne rosé benefits from 15-minute settling after opening.</li>

  <li><strong>Use Bordeaux-Style Glasses for Complex Rosés</strong> - While flutes work for rosé Champagne, still rosés perform best in medium-bowl glasses with slight inward taper. This shape concentrates the wine's often-subtle aromatics while providing enough surface area for proper aeration. Avoid wide Burgundy bowls that dissipate rosé's delicate nose, and never use thick-rimmed glasses that interfere with the wine's crisp finish.</li>

  <li><strong>Follow the 18-Month Freshness Rule</strong> - Most rosés peak within 6-12 months of vintage date and decline rapidly after 18 months. Check the back label for bottling date—wines bottled more than 6 months after harvest often show diminished fruit. Notable exceptions include Bandol rosé (ages 2-3 years), vintage rosé Champagne (5-10 years), and Tavel (up to 3 years due to higher tannin structure).</li>

  <li><strong>Identify Serious Rosés by Their Texture</strong> - Premium rosés exhibit a subtle textural weight from brief skin contact and proper lees aging. Look for wines with gentle grip on the mid-palate—not aggressive tannins, but noticeable structure. Wines that taste purely acidic and watery lack this complexity. Provence rosés from old-vine Mourvèdre show this texture beautifully, as do Loire Cabernet Franc rosés.</li>

  <li><strong>Match Rosé Style to Season and Food</strong> - Light, dry rosés (Provence style) excel in spring with seafood and salads, while fuller-bodied rosés (Bandol, Rioja) handle summer grilling and heartier fare. Semi-dry rosés complement spicy Asian cuisine year-round. Reserve vintage rosé Champagne for autumn celebrations when its developed complexity shines alongside richer dishes.</li>

  <li><strong>Storage Matters More Than You Think</strong> - Rosé's pale color offers little UV protection—store bottles in complete darkness or wrapped in tissue. Temperature fluctuations above 65°F accelerate aging and create cooked flavors. If buying for future consumption, choose bottles with dark glass and avoid any stored under bright retail lighting. Once opened, rosé maintains quality for only 2-3 days refrigerated, compared to 3-5 days for robust reds.</li>
