<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Most rosé wines are crafted for immediate enjoyment, but understanding their aging potential helps maximize your investment and drinking pleasure.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Style</h3>

<p><strong>Provence and high-end rosés</strong> from producers like Domaine Tempier or Château d'Esclans can develop beautifully for 3-5 years, gaining complexity while retaining freshness. <strong>Champagne rosé</strong> and serious sparkling wines age gracefully for 5-8 years, developing toasty, brioche notes alongside evolved fruit.</p>

<p><strong>Everyday rosés</strong> from regions like Languedoc or Spanish Rosado peak within 12-18 months, when their vibrant strawberry and citrus notes shine brightest. <strong>Rosé Burgundy</strong> and Sancerre rosé can reward patience for 2-4 years, developing mineral complexity and deeper fruit concentration.</p>

<h3>Evolution Over Time</h3>

<p>Well-made rosés evolve from bright berry and floral notes toward more complex profiles featuring dried herbs, white pepper, and subtle honey undertones. The wine's pale salmon hue may deepen slightly to copper-pink, while maintaining structural integrity through balanced acidity.</p>

<h3>Proper Storage Requirements</h3>

<p>Store rosé at consistent <strong>55-58°F</strong> with 60-70% humidity in a dark environment. Unlike reds, rosés should be consumed relatively young, making proper storage even more critical to preserve their delicate fruit character and prevent premature oxidation.</p>

<h3>Quality Indicators</h3>

<p><strong>Proper aging signs</strong> include integrated aromatics, silky texture development, and enhanced mineral notes. <strong>Warning signs of spoilage</strong> include browning color (beyond light copper tones), flat fruit character, excessive oxidation aromas resembling sherry, or loss of the wine's characteristic freshness and acidity that defines quality rosé.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between dry and sweet rosé wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Dry rosé contains less than 4 grams of residual sugar per liter and showcases crisp acidity with mineral notes, while sweet rosé (like White Zinfandel) contains 12+ grams of residual sugar, creating a softer, fruit-forward profile. Most premium rosé from Provence, Bandol, and Loire Valley are bone dry, emphasizing terroir and grape character rather than sweetness. The best way to identify style is to check the alcohol level—dry rosé typically ranges from 11.5-13.5% ABV, while sweet versions often fall below 11%.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
