    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should rosé wine be served as cold as white wine or warmer like red wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve rosé between 45-50°F (7-10°C), slightly warmer than most white wines but cooler than reds. This temperature preserves the wine's delicate aromatics while allowing its subtle fruit flavors and mineral complexity to shine through. Over-chilling rosé below 40°F mutes its flavor profile, while serving above 55°F can make it taste flabby and lose its refreshing character that makes rosé so appealing.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Why do some rosé wines cost $15 while others cost $50 or more?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Premium rosé commands higher prices due to factors like prestigious terroir (Provence's Bandol AOC), low-yield vineyard practices, and extended lees aging that adds complexity. Expensive rosé often comes from old vines, hand-harvested grapes, and careful saignée or direct press methods that require more labor and expertise. Mass-produced rosé uses higher yields, machine harvesting, and rapid fermentation techniques that prioritize volume over complexity, resulting in simpler wines at lower price points.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when buying rosé wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is buying rosé that's more than 18 months old, as most rosé wines are designed for immediate consumption and lose their fresh, vibrant character with age. Always check the vintage date and choose the most recent year available, especially for Provence rosé, Pinot Grigio rosé, and Sancerre rosé. Another major error is assuming all rosé is sweet—many people miss out on exceptional dry rosé because they expect cloying sweetness based on outdated perceptions.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can rosé wine be aged like red or white wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most rosé wines are not designed for aging and should be consumed within 1-2 years of vintage for optimal freshness and fruit character. However, exceptional rosé from producers like Domaine Tempier (Bandol), Château Simone, or premium Tavel can develop beautifully for 3-5 years, gaining complexity and savory notes. These age-worthy rosé typically have higher tannin content, lower pH, and come from prestigious appellations with structured winemaking approaches that differ from typical "drink now" styles.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is rosé wine a good choice for beginners who are just learning about wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Rosé is excellent for wine beginners because it bridges the gap between white and red wines, offering approachable fruit flavors without overwhelming tannins or excessive acidity. The visual appeal and food-friendly nature make rosé less intimidating than complex reds, while dry Provence styles introduce beginners to mineral complexity and terroir concepts. Start with well-known producers like Whispering Angel, Miraval, or AIX to experience quality benchmarks before exploring more adventurous regions like Corsica or Spain.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the best alternatives if I can't find good French Provence rosé?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Excellent Provence-style alternatives include Spanish Garnacha rosé from Navarra, Italian Cerasuolo d'Abruzzo from Montepulciano grapes, and Austrian rosé from Zweigelt or Pinot Noir. California producers like Stolpman, Bedrock, and Arnot-Roberts create outstanding dry rosé using Provence techniques with local grapes. For similar pale color and mineral-driven profiles, look for rosé from Portugal's Vinho Verde region or Greek Roditis rosé, which offer exceptional value and comparable elegance to premium Provence bottlings.</p>
  </div>
